<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="167" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="1.[307,1139,1268,1582]" pageId="1" pageNumber="167">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[333,446,1294,1315]" pageId="1" pageNumber="167">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Coraebine, small, subcylindrical, flattened above and strongly convex below, both longitudinally and latitudinally appearing navicular from the side; surface asperate; narrow vittae and one elytral fascia of dense setae decorate dorsal surface; antennae serrate from antennamere 4; prosternum lacking mentonniere; elytral apices each with one sutural tooth; pygidium with single projecting medial spine; ventral pulvilli on four basal tarsomeres, claws appendiculate.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="168" pageId="1" pageNumber="167" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="1.[307,1139,1268,1582]" pageId="1" pageNumber="167">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[333,468,1481,1502]" pageId="1" pageNumber="167">Description.</emphasis>
Head deeply emaginate between eyes on frontovertex, with one pair of produced lateral lobes projecting anteriorly beyond margin of eyes; frontoclypeus entire; antennal cavities small, only moderately separated by narrow parallel足sided portion of frontoclypeus; lateral portion of clypeus trans足
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[307,856,1634,1650]" box="[307,856,1634,1650]" pageId="1" pageNumber="167">
<superScript attach="left" box="[307,313,1634,1644]" fontSize="4" pageId="1" pageNumber="167">1</superScript>
2nd contribution to the understanding of Madagascan 
<taxonomicName box="[769,852,1634,1650]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="167" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Coraebini">Coraebini</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[705,740,1681,1700]" box="[705,740,1681,1700]" pageId="1" pageNumber="167">167</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[279,1113,271,1012]" pageId="2" pageNumber="168">versely excavated for basal antennameres in repose; pronotum widest near midpoint, subquadrate, anterior margin arcuate medially, posterior margin bisinuate, lateral margins broadly arcuate, entirely carinate; disk entire, flattened; scutellum subtriangular; elytra wider opposite humeri than pronotum; gradually narrowing to rounded apices; epipleura well足developed, nearly entire; prosternum with anterior margin feebly emarginate; process feebly expanded posterior to procoxae; metacoxal plate transverse posteriorly; abdominal sterna 1 and 2 subequal, 3 and 4 shorter than 2, 5 longer than 4, not sexually modified; femora subparallel; tibiae feebly arcuate basally.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="168" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="2.[279,1113,271,1012]" pageId="2" pageNumber="168">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[306,433,510,531]" pageId="2" pageNumber="168">Etymology.</emphasis>
This new monotypic genus is defined as masculine and the name is chosen to honor Richard P. Fall, as mentioned above.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="168" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="2.[279,1113,271,1012]" pageId="2" pageNumber="168">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[306,414,564,585]" pageId="2" pageNumber="168">Remarks.</emphasis>
In my evolving understanding of the Madagascan Coraebina, placement within the as yet unstructured ordering of the known fauna is rather arbitrary, as even genus足group definition is premature. From the extant taxa, it belongs to Group 2 of three groups of genera defined by the configuration of the head topography, which was used in the initial sorting of the thousands of specimens in the Paris Museum collection by the late A. Descarpentries. Group 1 has the frons relatively evenly transverse or only feebly emarginate between the eyes, 
<emphasis box="[477,677,751,772]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="168">e.g., Entomogaster</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Saunders" box="[685,861,751,772]" pageId="2" pageNumber="168" refId="ref2410" refString="Saunders, E. 1871. Catalogus Buprestidarum Synonymicus et Systematicus. J. Janson, London. 171 pp." type="book" year="1871">Saunders (1871)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Obenberger (1942)" authorityName="Obenberger" authorityYear="1942" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Midongya" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="168" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[874,980,751,772]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="168">Midongya</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Obenberger" pageId="2" pageNumber="168" pagination="7 - 13" refId="ref2377" refString="Obenberger, J. 1942. De Agrilinorum unsulae Madagascaris generibus novis quinque. Pet novych rodu Agrilinu z ostrova Madagascaru. Acta Entomologica Musei Nationalis Pragae 20: 7 - 13." type="journal article" year="1942">Obenberger (1942)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Obenberger (1931)" authorityName="Obenberger" authorityYear="1931" box="[364,711,777,799]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Paranastella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="168" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[364,499,778,799]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="168">Paranastella</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Obenberger" box="[507,711,777,798]" pageId="2" pageNumber="168" pagination="175 - 201" refId="ref2354" refString="Obenberger, J. 1931. Studien uber die aethiopischen Buprestiden I. Folia Zoologica et Hydrobiologica 2: 175 - 201." type="journal article" year="1931">Obenberger (1931)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
; Group 2 has the frons more strongly depressed between a single pair of lobes projecting beyond the outline of the eyes, 
<emphasis box="[343,525,831,852]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="168">e.g., Antanambia</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Descarpentries" box="[535,773,831,852]" pageId="2" pageNumber="168" pagination="19 - 25" refId="ref2154" refString="Descarpentries, A. 1975. Deux nouveaux genres de Buprestidae de Madagascar [Col.]. Bulletin de la Societe Entomologique de France 80: 19 - 25." type="journal article" year="1975">Descarpentries (1975)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Kerremans (1893)" authorityName="Kerremans" authorityYear="1893" box="[787,1107,831,852]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Chloricala" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="168" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[787,900,831,852]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="168">Chloricala</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Kerremans" box="[911,1107,831,852]" pageId="2" pageNumber="168" pagination="94 - 122" refId="ref2254" refString="Kerremans, C. 1893. Essai de groupement des Buprestides. Annales de la Societe Entomologique de Belgique 37: 94 - 122." type="journal article" year="1893">Kerremans (1893)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Deyrolle (1864)" authorityName="Deyrolle" authorityYear="1864" box="[279,543,857,879]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Sambus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="168" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[279,360,858,879]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="168">Sambus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Deyrolle &amp; Description des Buprestides de la Malaisie" box="[370,543,857,878]" pageId="2" pageNumber="168" pagination="1 - 312" refId="ref2185" refString="Deyrolle, H. 1864. Description des Buprestides de la Malaisie recueilles par M. Wallace. Annales de la Societe Entomologique de Belgique 8: 1 - 312." type="journal article" year="1864">Deyrolle (1864)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
; and Group 3 has two pair of frontal turbercles, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="168">e.g., Angatra</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Descarpentries" box="[377,617,884,905]" pageId="2" pageNumber="168" pagination="599 - 602" refId="ref2118" refString="Descarpentries, A. 1969. Deux Buprestides inedits de Madagascar appartenant a la tribu des Coraebini [Col.]. Bulletin de Madagascar 19 (277 - 278): 599 - 602." type="journal article" year="1969">Descarpentries (1969)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Obenberger (1942)" authorityName="Obenberger" authorityYear="1942" box="[633,988,884,905]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Mandritsaria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="168" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[633,772,884,905]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="168">Mandritsaria</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Obenberger" box="[784,988,884,905]" pageId="2" pageNumber="168" pagination="7 - 13" refId="ref2377" refString="Obenberger, J. 1942. De Agrilinorum unsulae Madagascaris generibus novis quinque. Pet novych rodu Agrilinu z ostrova Madagascaru. Acta Entomologica Musei Nationalis Pragae 20: 7 - 13." type="journal article" year="1942">Obenberger (1942)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Kerremans (1900)" authorityName="Kerremans" authorityYear="1900" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Paradora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="168" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="168">Paradora</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Kerremans" box="[339,536,911,932]" pageId="2" pageNumber="168" pagination="282 - 351" refId="ref2279" refString="Kerremans, C. 1900. Buprestides nouveaux et remarques synonymiques. Annales de la Societe Entomologique de Belgique 44: 282 - 351." type="journal article" year="1900">Kerremans (1900)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bellamy" authorityYear="2001" box="[549,649,911,932]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Falliellus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="168" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[549,649,911,932]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="168">Falliellus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs immediately from all known Madagascan coraebines by the combination of surface sculpture and vestiture design, the navicular appearance when viewed laterally and the pair of apical elytral teeth.
</paragraph>
